unterVec()`, etc. For example, in `discovery/metrics.go:34-73`, the `NewManagerMetrics()` function creates individual metrics and stores them in a `Metrics` struct.\n\n2. **Explicit Registration**: Created metrics are registered individually by iterating through a list of collectors and calling `registerer.Register()` on each (discovery/metrics.go:83-87). This gives fine-grained control over what gets registered.\n\n3. **Metric Registerer Pattern**: Prometheus introduces a helper in `discovery/azure/metrics.go:48-51` that wraps multiple collectors with `discovery.NewMetricRegisterer()`, providing a register/unregister interface while maintaining the underlying prometheus.Registerer.\n\n4. **Main Server Setup**: In `cmd/prometheus/main.go`, the global registry is used directly. Metrics like `configSuccess` (line 131) and `configSuccessTime` (line 135) are created as package-level variables and registered via `prometheus.MustRegister()` (lines 1116-1117).\n\n### Grafana/Grafana\nGrafana combines package-level metric declarations with a centralized initialization and registration strategy:\n\n1. **Package-Level Declarations**: In `pkg/infra/metrics/metrics.go`, all metrics are declared as module-level variables (lines 17-232). Examples include `MInstanceStart` (line 19), `MPageStatus` (line 22), and many Counter/Gauge/Summary/Histogram types.\n\n2. **init() Function Initialization**: The `init()` function (metrics.go:262-718) initializes all metric objects with specific options. Each metric is created with appropriate options including namespace, subsystem, and help text.\n\n3. **Centralized Registration**: The `initMetricVars()` function (metrics.go:785-859) takes a `prometheus.Registerer` and registers all initialized metrics via `reg.MustRegister()` in a single batch call (lines 786-858).\n\n4. **Service-Based Initialization**: The `InternalMetricsService` is provided via dependency injection in `pkg/infra/metrics/service.go:ProvideService()` (line 29), which calls `initMetricVars(reg)` to register metrics with the injected registerer. The service also provides `ProvideRegisterer()` and `ProvideGatherer()` functions (lines 65-72) that wrap the Kubernetes legacy registry with custom logic like metric name prefix addition.\n\n### Key Differences\n\n- **Kubernetes** emphasizes version-aware, stability-level-based metric registration with a custom wrapper around the prometheus registry, supporting metric deprecation.\n- **Prometheus** uses the standard prometheus client library patterns directly, with explicit registration of individual or grouped metrics.\n- **Grafana** centralizes all metric definitions and registration in a single package with init-time initialization and service-based dependency injection, even wrapping the Kubernetes registry with its own prefix logic.\n\n### Exposure Patterns\n\nAll three projects expose metrics via HTTP handlers:\n- **Kubernetes**: `legacyregistry.Handler()` (legacyregistry/registry.go:63-65) returns a wrapped `promhttp.Handler`\n- **Prometheus**: Uses `prometheus.DefaultRegisterer` and HTTP handlers for metrics endpoint\n- **Grafana**: Uses `ProvideGatherer()` (service.go:69-72) which combines the Kubernetes registry gatherer with the prometheus DefaultGatherer"
